In this year’s robot, a lot of teams have a shaft blocking mechanisms like a wrist on the elevator, and here are two solutions for it:

  1. Graph Machine

similar to this but with DFS.

One issue with this is that it takes too much time to think about how to model FSM with it, which causes code ambiguity when having a bunch of edges.

Therefore, over the past two days, the following method was created:

  1. Collision Detector (2D)

to make it work for every mechanism (except arms that can extend as far I know), this framework contains three main concepts:
Scene, AOR (axis of rotation) and OBB (Oriented Bounding Box)
more terms:
center (local offset): the translation from AOR to bounding box
global offset: the translation from AOR to the center of scene (0, 0)
local rotation: the rotation of the box with respect to itself
global rotation: the rotation of AOR

Scene is where you can add AORs into it, one way to model wrist on elevator is add one AOR representing the axis of rotation of arm and
use the elevator’s height and measurements from cad to get the Global Offset of the AOR. Arm’s angle would be the global rotation.

aor_offset992×1102 208 KB

Global Offset/Rotation can be passed in an array which supports more than one AOR within a scene.

For each AOR, mechanisms can be approximate with rectangles with different sizes (because it’s easier to consider boxes when detecting collision), and center (local offset) would be the distence from AOR to the center of the rectangle.

aor1120×1284 129 KB

Obstacles can just be added as rectangle too.

Result:
Working Space (Domain)

workspace1601×731 113 KB

Nextstep: Although current project might continue with a state‑machine approach, those interested in this alternative (might requires a spare co-processor like OrangePi 5) can explore the following to make it work on actual robot:

  • MinimumSnap
  • Lagrange Interpolate
  • Use power-torque curve (as while as MOI) to estimade max accleration while having voltage sag, I dont know if theres any way onshape gives it, if not use parallel axis theorem
  • If it runs on co-processor but your team use C++, try WebSocket
